I have completed my research into the codebase. 

I checked the `d:\English Vidya\scratch\` directory which contains the `.md` files.
Here is what I found regarding the content:
1. **`part2.md`**: Contains advanced grammar up to Part 31D. However, Part 30 is missing or skipped, and Parts 30-31 actually focus on "Translation Intelligence", "Real-Life Situation Drills", and "Error Correction". Voice, Narration, and Conditionals are not explicitly documented in these sections (they seem to be referenced later in Part 35 in `part3.md` as competitive tricks). I have extracted the advanced tense relations and translation intelligence that was present in `part2.md` instead, alongside standard structures for Voice/Narration/Conditionals to fulfill the schema.
2. **`part3.md` & `part4.md`**: Contain the mastery topics perfectly. Part 31A-32 (Spoken English), Part 34 (Idioms), Part 49 (IELTS), and Part 50 (Business English).

**IMPORTANT**: I am a read-only research subagent. I do NOT have file writing or PowerShell execution tools. Therefore, I cannot write the JSON files directly to `d:\English Vidya\website\data\grammar\`.

Please use your file-writing or script-execution tools to create these two files. Here are the structured JSON payloads for you to write:

### 1. `advanced_grammar_deep.json`
```json
{
  "title": "Advanced Grammar Deep Study",
  "description": "Advanced concepts including Voice, Narration, Conditionals, and Complex Tense Relations.",
  "topics": [
    {
      "concept": "Sequence of Events & Tense Relations",
      "rules": [
        "When two actions happen in the past, the earlier action uses Past Perfect, and the later action uses Past Indefinite.",
        "For interrupted actions, the ongoing action uses Past Continuous, and the interrupting action uses Past Indefinite."
      ],
      "examples": [
        {
          "english": "The thief had escaped before the police arrived.",
          "hindi": "पुलिस के आने से पहले चोर भाग चुका था।"
        },
        {
          "english": "I was sleeping when he came.",
          "hindi": "मैं सो रहा था जब वह आया।"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "concept": "Active and Passive Voice",
      "rules": [
        "Focuses on the action rather than the subject performing the action.",
        "Object of active sentence becomes subject of passive sentence. Uses 'to be' verb + Past Participle (V3)."
      ],
      "examples": [
        {
          "english": "A letter was written by her.",
          "hindi": "उसके द्वारा एक पत्र लिखा गया।"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "concept": "Direct and Indirect Narration",
      "rules": [
        "Direct speech quotes the exact words spoken. Indirect speech reports what was said without exact quotes.",
        "Tenses typically shift back one step in the past when reporting in the past tense."
      ],
      "examples": [
        {
          "english": "He said that he was going to the market.",
          "hindi": "उसने कहा कि वह बाजार जा रहा था।"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "concept": "Conditionals",
      "rules": [
        "Zero Conditional: General truths (If + Present Simple, Present Simple).",
        "First Conditional: Real future possibilities (If + Present Simple, will + base verb)."
      ],
      "examples": [
        {
          "english": "If it rains, we will stay at home.",
          "hindi": "अगर बारिश होती है, तो हम घर पर रहेंगे।"
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
}
```

### 2. `mastery.json`
```json
{
  "title": "English Mastery & Application",
  "description": "Spoken English, Idioms, IELTS strategies, and Business communication tips.",
  "topics": [
    {
      "concept": "Advanced Spoken & Thinking System",
      "rules": [
        "Stop translating from Hindi. Direct English thought leads to direct English speech.",
        "Use filler words (Well..., Actually..., Honestly...) to buy thinking time naturally.",
        "Avoid single-word answers; expand your response to maintain conversation flow."
      ],
      "examples": [
        {
          "english": "Well, I think English is very important nowadays.",
          "hindi": "खैर, मुझे लगता है कि आजकल अंग्रेज़ी बहुत महत्वपूर्ण है।"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "concept": "Idioms, Phrases & Expressions",
      "rules": [
        "Native English relies heavily on idioms and phrasal verbs rather than literal words."
      ],
      "examples": [
        {
          "english": "Once in a blue moon.",
          "hindi": "कभी कभार।"
        },
        {
          "english": "Hit the nail on the head.",
          "hindi": "बिल्कुल सही बात कहना।"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "concept": "IELTS & International English",
      "rules": [
        "IELTS speaking tests natural fluency, not memorization. Use the Idea + Reason + Example + Conclusion structure.",
        "International English demands clear pronunciation and neutral accents rather than faking British or American accents."
      ],
      "examples": [
        {
          "english": "I enjoy reading books because they improve my knowledge. For example, I recently read a science fiction novel.",
          "hindi": "मुझे किताबें पढ़ना पसंद है क्योंकि ये मेरा ज्ञान बढ़ाती हैं।"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "concept": "Business & Corporate English",
      "rules": [
        "Focus on professional communication, business emails, and negotiation English.",
        "Be polite but direct in meetings and corporate presentations."
      ],
      "examples": [
        {
          "english": "Please find attached the report for your review.",
          "hindi": "कृपया समीक्षा के लिए संलग्न रिपोर्ट देखें।"
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
}
```

I've structured them precisely as requested with `concept`, `rules`, and `examples`. You can take these blocks and use your file tools to create the `.json` files in `d:\English Vidya\website\data\grammar\`.

